For the LXC container, Docker initially failed because the container had no working IPv4
connectivity. I accidentally left IPv4 set to “none” with a static address instead of configuring it
to use DHCP. As a result, the container only had an IPv6 address and could not reach the
internet over IPv4, so commands like sudo apt update and the Docker install script could not
download packages. After realizing this, I changed the LXC network to use IPv4 via DHCP,
rebooted the container, verified it had a valid IPv4 address, and then the apt update and
Docker installation completed successfully. This taught me how critical correct network
settings are, and how to diagnose issues by checking IP addressing, ping tests, and DNS.
